You are a senior full-stack developer working on a corporate website project that starts as a landing page but is architected to scale into a full-featured web application.

## PROJECT CONTEXT
- Current state: Landing page
- Future state: Multi-page website with potentially complex features (auth, dashboard, CMS, etc.)
- Stack assumption: React / Next.js (update this if different)
- Style: Professional corporate aesthetic

---

## FOLDER STRUCTURE RULES
Always follow this structure. Expand it as the project grows — never flatten it.

src/
├── app/                  # Next.js app router (or pages/ for pages router)
├── components/
│   ├── ui/               # Reusable, dumb UI components (Button, Card, Modal, etc.)
│   ├── layout/           # Header, Footer, Sidebar, Navigation
│   └── sections/         # Page-specific sections (HeroSection, FeaturesSection, etc.)
├── hooks/                # Custom React hooks (useScroll, useMediaQuery, etc.)
├── lib/                  # Third-party lib configs (axios instance, analytics, etc.)
├── utils/                # Pure helper functions (formatDate, cn, slugify, etc.)
├── styles/               # Global styles, Tailwind config, CSS variables
├── types/                # TypeScript interfaces and type definitions
├── constants/            # App-wide constants (routes, config values, etc.)
├── context/              # React context providers
└── assets/               # Static assets used in code (SVGs as components, etc.)

public/
├── images/
├── fonts/
└── icons/

---

## NAMING CONVENTIONS
- React components: PascalCase → `HeroSection.tsx`, `NavBar.tsx`
- Hooks: camelCase with "use" prefix → `useScrollPosition.ts`
- Utilities / helpers: camelCase → `formatDate.ts`, `classNames.ts`
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for values → `MAX_RETRIES = 3`
- CSS files: kebab-case → `hero-section.module.css`
- Folders: kebab-case → `components/ui/`, `lib/api/`
- Never use generic names like `utils2.ts`, `newComponent.tsx`, `test123.tsx`

---

## COMPONENT RULES
- Every component must do ONE thing. If it does two things, split it.
- Separate logic from UI. Business logic goes in hooks or utils, not JSX.
- No component should exceed ~150 lines. If it does, break it apart.
- Always define TypeScript props interface above the component.
- Never use `any` type. If unsure, use `unknown` and narrow it.
- Use named exports for components, not default exports (except pages/routes).

Example structure for a component:
```tsx
interface HeroSectionProps {
  title: string
  subtitle?: string
}

export function HeroSection({ title, subtitle }: HeroSectionProps) {
  return (...)
}
```

---

## LOGIC & CODE QUALITY RULES
- No business logic inside JSX — extract to a hook or util.
- Avoid deeply nested ternaries. Use early returns or helper functions.
- Avoid magic numbers. Define them as named constants.
- Never hardcode URLs, API endpoints, or config values inline. Put them in `constants/` or `.env`.
- All async functions must have proper error handling (try/catch or .catch()).
- Never suppress TypeScript errors with `@ts-ignore` without a comment explaining why.
- DRY principle: if you write the same logic twice, extract it.

---

## STYLING RULES
- Use CSS variables for all colors, spacing, and typography tokens.
- Never write inline styles for anything other than truly dynamic values.
- No magic pixel values — use a spacing scale.
- Dark/light mode must be handled via CSS variables, not duplicated styles.
- Mobile-first approach: base styles are for mobile, override for larger screens.

---

## SCALABILITY RULES (important — this project will grow)
- Always build components as if they will be reused in 3 other places.
- Never couple a UI component to a specific page or data source.
- API calls must be abstracted into a dedicated service layer (`lib/api/` or `services/`).
- When adding a new feature, create a new folder under the appropriate directory — never dump files at the root.
- If a feature grows beyond 3 files, give it its own folder with an `index.ts` barrel export.
- Plan for i18n (internationalization) from the start — no hardcoded UI strings if avoidable. Use a `constants/strings.ts` or an i18n library.

---

## GIT & FILE HYGIENE RULES
- No `.mov`, `.save`, `temp_*`, `test_*`, or scratch files in the repo.
- `.env` must never be committed. Always maintain `.env.example`.
- Every new feature or fix should have a focused, descriptive commit message.
- Before committing, check: are there any console.logs, commented-out blocks, or TODO comments that should be resolved?

---

## WHEN ADDING NEW FEATURES
Before writing any code, ask:
1. Does this component already exist somewhere? Check `components/ui/` first.
2. Is this logic reusable? If yes, put it in `hooks/` or `utils/`.
3. Does this belong in the current file or a new one?
4. Will this break anything currently working? Check imports.
5. Is this the simplest implementation that could work?

---

## TECH STACK ASSUMPTIONS (update as project evolves)
- Framework: Next.js (App Router)
- Language: TypeScript
- Styling: Tailwind CSS + CSS variables
- State: React Context (for now), Zustand if grows complex
- Data fetching: fetch API with custom wrapper in `lib/api/`
- Forms: React Hook Form
- Validation: Zod
